1790	Oscar Pistorius as a child
1826	The life of Pistorius can be seen in two arcs. There is one story of
1895	extraordinary determination - how this boy with no evident running talent at
1972	12 somehow scaled the heights of sport in just a few years. But the second
2047	story is how that innocent boy became, as weeks of testimony in court
2117	suggested, a man plagued by his temper, with a reckless love for guns and
2191	speed - condemned by the judge as "negligent" when he pulled the trigger.
2274	In one of Oscar's earliest memories, he hurtled down a hill near his home, in
2352	his brother Carl's go-kart, as the two of them began a lifelong passion for
2428	speed - they were "adrenalin junkies", Pistorius later wrote in his
2496	autobiography, Blade Runner.
2534	As the wall at the bottom of the hill loomed in front of them, with no brakes
2612	on the kart, Carl grabbed Oscar's prosthetic leg, yanked it off and pushed it
2690	into the wheel to bring the vehicle to a sudden stop.
2753	This narrow escape did nothing to dampen his new addiction - aged four he was
2831	riding mini-motorbikes. Soon after he was racing his father at go-karting.
2906	Aged 15, he was driving his brother's Golf, and as an adult a speedboating
2981	accident nearly ended his career.
3024	This hotheaded adventurousness in the young boy was partly encouraged by his
3101	family, who were determined that his disability would not make him a spectator
3180	in life. In the Pistorius family, who lived in a comfortable part of
3249	Johannesburg, no-one was allowed to say "I can't."
3309	Oscar and his mother
3339	Born with no fibulas - the smaller of the two lower leg bones - Oscar's legs
3416	were amputated below the knee when he was 11 months old. Six months later, he
3494	received his first prosthetics, a defining moment in his life, he later said.
3572	This plaster and mesh fitted with a lycra "skin" was a liberation.
3639	Immediately, he says, he felt invincible and his energy was boundless.
3719	"I believe that it was at this time in my life that my personality was shaped,
3798	and that my family was instrumental in laying the foundation stones of my
3872	competitive nature, and of the man that I am today," he wrote in Blade Runner.
3960	His mother was a huge influence. She put inspirational notes into the
4030	lunchboxes of her children, and one letter she wrote for him he still keeps:
4107	"The real loser is never the person who crosses the finishing line last. The
4184	real loser is the person who sits on the side, the person who does not even
4260	try to compete."
4286	Getting ready for school, she would say: "Carl, put on your shoes. Oscar, put
4364	on your legs." He was different, but equal.
